{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_eliot_ver01/data/sn86091188/00295869124/1907121901/0806.xml":{"full_text":"FAVOR OFJIASIK (URRENOf!\nlire's Marline Advances Some Oood Ideas on tie Financial\niQueston and Mucb from tde Standpoint o! a Ricb Han.\nj\nj\nI\n\ne always beeD in favor of an\ncurrency, just as I wiuld be\nor of any other good machine\nwould facilitate production,\na steair, engine or a tcle\niet I am not so foolish as to\nthe introduction of a better\nto facilitate production un\n^uitalisiu is going to save us\n|l, e condition of overproduc\nThe financial system which\nin the United States is of a\nprimitive nature, and the\nI we improve it, the belter it\nfor most everybody, exactly\n(sooner we improve any other\nlery of production and ex\njuoticy question is not a ditll\nto understand, although, as\ner of fact, very few seem to\nlaud it. In normal times,\nLdiviiiual, and every business\n|ti m. and every bank, keeps\nmoney in hand as possible,\nddual doesn't care to carry\naround in his pocket than\nsarv: first, because lie might\nhe robbed: second, because\nfs to have his money out at\nThe business corporations\nsi as little in the bank as\nbecause every dollar that\ne is idle and not earning any\nIml tlie bank in turn, keeps\nmoney in its vaults to meet\nsuris of depositors as possible,\nI every dollar lying there rep\nno income.\n(Tnancial system of the coun\nliiiilar to that of the water\n|f a city which has no reser\nnormai times, the city gets\nright; hut if there is a fire\n|enly there e\u00fbmes a great de\nwater, the pipes run dry\nbity burns up. No individu\n\nI\n\n\n\nj\n\nI\nNOTICE\nbe following will be the prices\n|oal, commencing Sept. 1st.\nat the mine $4.00 per ton\nrun, delivered\u20145.00\nCoal 6.00\norders will be promptly\nat the above prices.\nH. G. KING.\nFRANK R. REHMENKLAU\n\ns a :r\nMips* A W\u00ab\u2122\nTAXIDERMIST\nSpecimens\"of all kinds of animals\nand birds mounted true to nature.\nII Years Successful Experience.\nj If you expect to have any work in\ni this line, call on or address' me at\nSalmon, Idaho.\nStudio in the\nNutz Building.\nAIL WORK GUARANTEED.\n\nThe\ny Livry stable\nG. Mathewson, Prop.\nCarriages and Conveyances\nPack and Saddle Horses\nHa> and Grain for Sale at all Times\nCall at the Bi^ Red Barn\nSfreer, Salmon Idaho\nal could afford to keep a private res\nervoir with enough water on band to\n.save the city from destruction. To\nI keep such a reservoir must be the\nfunction of the city itself for the\nbenefit of all.\nWhen we have a fall in the stock\nmarket everybody wants money,\nand, inasmuch as everybody has been\nkeeping on hand the very smallest\namount possible, the increased de\nmand finds ho large reservoir to feed\nit. Then there is a panic. The peo\npie are so terror-strioken that they\nill increase the amount of money\nthey have previouisy been holding by\nhoarding it in safe deposit vaults.\nTo remedy this, what is wanted is a\npublic reservoir of money to draw up\njon in panic times, just exactly as a\ncity wants a large public reservoir of\nwater tc draw upon in case of a big\nfire. The private individual will not\nkeep on hand money for such einer\ngencies. It would take too much\ncapital for any individual to supply,\nfor even Morgan or Rockefeller, and\nthen, as a matter of fact, the knowl\nedge that such an amount was on\nhand, would take away its profit\nhearing capacity if Morgan should\nhold money expecting a panic, be\ncause the knowledge of its being on\nhand would, in Itself, prevent a panic\nand defeat his aim. No one but the\ngovrenment could have any unselfish\nmotive for keeping a supply of the\ncirculaitng medium on hand to meet\na\" emergency call. The government\nshould keep emergency money on\nhand, in the shape of its paper obli\ngations, that is, say, legal tender\nnotes, for paper would accomplish\ntire saiue object and witli less ex\npense and labor than gold. Inas\nmuch as tills emergency money\nwould only be issued on good secur\nty Dd at sufficient high rate of\nInterest to induce its return at an\nearly period, and furthermore, as\nthis emergency currency would be re\ndet niable In gold, there Is no reason\nwhy sucli an emergency currency, is\nsued by the government, should not\nsolve rbe currency problem and pre\nvent absolutely any recurrence of a\nfinancial panic. If we don't bave\nan elaatic currency measure passed\nby congress, and have It at once. It\nmeans a still greater condition of\nfinancial and industrial ebaos than 1\nhave heretofore prophesied, and the\naccentuation of the Unemployed prob\nlem. While 1 foresee that the end\nof the present capitalist system is\nnear at hand, at the same time, I\nam not so foolish as not to wisli tlie\nintroduction of any process, which\nwill help out the present system In\nthe interim when we are transform\ning our empetitive system Into tlie\nco-operative system, and I therefore\nstrongly urge the adoption of a sys\ntem of elastic currency. All Euro\npean countries and Canada, have\nelastic currencies, America alone is\nbenind.\nAs to the question as to whom his\ncurrency shall be issued, and tlie raie\nof interest that should be settled up\non, the broad question that anybody\ncan have It who will take a sufficient\nquantity to pay the government to\ninvestigate his security, and the in\nterest should he sufficiently high to\ninduce a very speedy retirement of\nthis merely emergency currency.\nBold is unquestionably the best basis\nfor our medium of exchange, and in\nordinary times there should lie no\nnecessity of any other medium. But\nthere is no question tiiat an emer\ngency currency should lie Issued by\nthe government to meet such de\nmands as we are now having, and It\nis most important that congress pass\nan act at once, providing for such a\ncurrency.\nSuch emergency currency would\nnot he Hat currency, that is, currency\nwhich is merely the promise of tlie\ngovernment to pay a dollar at an In\ndefinite period and without any guar\nantee that the owner of this govern\nment certificate will ever get the dol\nlar that is promised Emergency\ncurrency, which 1 have proposed,\nshould always he on an equality with\ngold, and exchangeable for it. 1 rec\nognize as fully as anyone the fact\nthat any depreciation of the value of\nthe medium of exchange injures the\nworking man more than any other\nindividual, and I would be the last\nman to favor It.\nBut the introduction of emergency\ncurrency to give elasticity to our\nmedium of exchange would, in no\nsense, debase the value of the dollar\nas most certainly would have been\ndone by our following the men or of\nBryan and his free silver. Elastic\ncurrency such as I advocate is advo\ncated by practically every sane busi\nness man and banker in the United\nStates, and the only reason wc have\nnot had it long ago is because our\npoliticians have net had the brains\nto foresee that a financial panic like\nwe are having today would Inevitably\nbe the result of their ideas of either\nthe old-time greenback neglect and\nstupidity.\nHowever, even witli the most per\nfect system of elastic currency we\nnever could avoid the final collapse\nof capitalism, owing to overproduc\ntion and unemployment. The pres\nent financial panic has merely accel\nembed the industrial breakdown by a\nfew months. The people of America\nhave not yet commenced to fully re\nalize the extraordinary nature of the\nterrible industrial crisis which is fast\napproaching us. Most business men\nthink that the financial crisis, which\nis now with us, can be cured by the\nissuance of an elastic currency for\nthe government, and that when we\ncure our financial disorder that tlie\nindustrial disorder will automatically\nset itself aright. Those who are\nfamiliar with what I have been writ\ning in this magazine for so many\nyears, know that 1 have continually\nprophesied that the indust rial struc\nture was bound to collapse. A year\nago, Iasi November, 1 stated posi\ntively that we must have the collapse\nfor November, 1907. My prophecy\nhas come only too true. I said the\nindustrial crisis would precipitate\nthe financial crisis and the two to\ngether would bring us to industrial\nchaos. Shortly, my theory is, that\nowing to the fact that the working\nclasses, and for that matter a large\nnumber of other people, tlie small\nbusiness men the farmers and most\nof the professional men. only get for\ntheir services the minimum of sub\nsistence, and as the consumption of\nthe masses Is the measure of our\nlie\nJuly\nby\nis\ntion\nof\na\nton,\nnot\nS.\nti\nbe\nto\na\nf\nmarket we are always threatened\ni\n\ni\nwith the appearance of the problem\nI of overpioduction. A more correct\nstatement of tiie case Is that we are\ncontinually threatened with the\nproblem of underconsumtion. Tin\nsurplus yve have beeD producing has\nbeen used by the capitalist In build-j\ning more railroads and factories, and\nit was inevitable that as soon us lie\nrealized that more near railroads and j\n'new factories could not be run to a\nI profit, be would be sure to\nbuilding, and then we would have an\nuneuipioyed problem.\nThe Trust was the sign of a com-;\npleted structure and tlie panic i f to\ndar confirms the sign. The Trust\nwas much more Significant than Con-,\nsequential. j\nI will not go over this theory in j\ndetall as it is so very familiar to the\nreadere of tills magazine. However,\nI am republishing elsewhere some\nextracts from an article of mine\nwhich came out in Wilshire's Maga\nxine, in August, a year ago, entitled,\n\"The loom of 190\u00ab.\" which gives\nstriking confirmation of my prophecy\nDENVER IS THE \u00dcVENVIION an\nlie Natiomi committee Accepts He Otter of $100.000 lor He\nSession\u2014Spirltei Defeote Over Question ol Propriety.\na\nWashington, Dec. li\u2014After de\nciding to hold the next democratic\nnational convention at lienver and\nfiixing the date of tlie meeting for\nJuly 7, 1908, the democratic national\ncommitter late today entered on a\nspirited debate on the propriety Of\naccepting more of tlie $100,000 offered\nby Denver for the convention than\nis actually needed t<i pay tlie conven- j\ntion expenses in that city.\nThe opposition to the acceptance\nof the oontrlbutlo took the form of\na resolution by Representative (.'lay\nton, of Alabama, declining money\nnot actually needed for the con ven-1\ntion, but after a long debate tlfc res\nolutinn was laid on tlie table by a\nvote of 31 to 14,\nMr. Clayton, Representative John\nS. Williams, of Mississippi and Out. i\nlioke Smith, of Georgia, all spoke in 1\nfavor of the passage of tlie r\u00e9solu-\nti 0r _\nMr. Williams spoke in a similar i\nvein, as also did Mr. Clayton. i\nMr. Taggart advocated the accept\nance of the $100,000, saving It would\nbe needed now even worse than lt'\nwas needed in 1904, and that at that\ntime it would have heen practically\nimpossible to have opened head\nquarters for Judge Parker if they\nhad not iiad Hie extra money secured\nfrom St. Louis, where the cooven\ntion was held.\nSenator Stone, of Missouri, made*\u00bb\nlong speech in which he favoted the\nacceptance of the money.\nMr. Clayton declared tiiat accept\nance of this money would he In line\nwith the very practices In campaign\ncontributions that liarl been con\ndemned by tlie committee.\nMayor Tom Johnson advocated the\nacceptance of t lie money offered by\nDenver.\nSenator Tillman opposed the ac\nceptance of tlie money. \"Let the\nlocal democratic organization ol\nColorado,\" said lie, \"have the money\nto tight their next campaign.\"\nThe motion to table Mr. Clayton's\nmotion prevailed by the billowing\nvote: Yes. Colorado, Connecticut,\nlieleware, Georgia, Illinois, Indiana,\nIowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana,\nMaine, Maryland, Michigan, Mis\nsouri. Nebraska, New Hampshire,\nNew .ftrsey, New Mexico, New\nYork. Ohio, Bennsyslvanla, Rhode\nIsland, Tennessee, Texas, Washing\nton, West Virginia Wisconsin, Wyotu\nDistrict or Columbia, Alaska,\nIndian Territory: 31. Noes: Ala\nbama, Arizona. Florida. Idaho, Mas\nsachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi,\nNorth Carolina. Oregon. South Caro\nlina. South Dakota, Vermont, Vir\nginia, Porto Rico; 14.\nOn the first ballot Denver received\nthirty-two votes as against seventeen\nfor Louisville, five for Chicago and\none for St. Paul. July 7 was selected\nas tlie date for the convention after\na very biief discussion. Tlie com\nmittee held two sessions during the\nday and adjourned finally at six\no'clock.\nCharles W, Franklin, of Denver,\nwas the first speaker to he heard in\nadvocacy of the claims of any of the\ncities as a place for holding the con\nf one reads of today's panic.\nLet me make another prediction.\nBy tlie time this magazine reaches\nits readers, there will tie such a huge\nnumber of unemployed In every city\nof the country, that it will be obvious\nto many that charity and soup kiteh\nens are not going to meet the issue.\nThe people in Pittsburg must tie\nfed, and the food supply is in Chicago.\nPittsburg has no money to pay for\nfood because it is out of employment\nand draws no wages. Chicago will\nnot feed Pittsburg unless It is paid\nfor the food. What is to be done':\nWe can't let the million men atiout\nPittsburg starve, ami it is obvious\nthat we have no permanent method\nof getting ttie food from Chicago to\nthem unless we start -tlie wheels of\nindustry working again\nWe must gel flour and tieef loaded\non the train at Chicago and shipped\nto Pittsburg. How is tills to lie\ndone? 1 win not lie one train for one\nday that must be staried, but a traio\nevery dav, and it must lie kept\n(Indefinitely. The problem which\nwill confront the people in Hie Unit-[but\n,.,y states will be how to save a large\nnundier from starvation: starving,\nnot because there is a famine, but\nbecause there is too much, it seems\nto me. very likely, that the United\n'-tute-- government *iil fie called up\non to 'oad up trains \"I provisions In\nt p e West, comn ande**r the railroads,\nour n ,ju s> stock ya'ds. and nrlng the\ny IJO( j t tlie starving In the F\u00fcut.\nCompensation will be given, but tbat\nj*. settled later Work must be\nceaseprovided to the people In Pittsburg\nhat t )ev njay pay fur the food. It,\nis true that fora day or two, or for\na week, food could be given us a\nmatter \"f charity, but sooner or later\ntlie government will be face to face\nwith the arranging of Hie problem of\nj the exchange of la tor between the\nj West and East. It will be the ar\nranging of this problem. namely, to\npay Chicago and Minneapolis for its\nproducts by giving in exchange the\nproducts of Pennsylvania, ind the\nEast generally, that will be the first\n(step to the establishment of the\nsocialist republic in America. \u2014W'il\nshire s Magazine.\nventlon. The invitation, -.aid Mr.\nFranklin, was first suggested by the\nDenver Convention league Incurpur\nated for the purpose of bringing con\nvent ions to Denver. From Ual to 200\nm held there every year. ''The\npeople of IV-nver are enthusiastic\nabout conventions, and we have come\nhere with the money for Its ex\npenses,'' be said. He spoke of tlie\nample accommodations both In the\nmatter of hotels and the Auditorium,\nwhich he said was built by the city\na oust of \u2666.>.'>0.000, and was capable\nholding U.ooo persons,\nMr. Franklin made a strong point\ntbe climate of Denver. He dc\nclared the railroad facilities to tie\n(ample in every tespect.\nContinuing, Mr. F ranklin said that\ni since 1832 there lias not been a na\n1 tlonal convention held iieyoml the\ngeographical center of the t idled\nStates. He said the people of tlie\ni Fad heen paying the additional\ni lure to tlie eastern cities lor all these\nyears, and that It was now time to\n_\nhe01 th \u2022Vantage of the\nducwl rale, they would get If the\neUlt as U) botels\nconvention should lie located in Deo\nver.\nMr. Franklin said the Denver com\nuilHee nad *i<m,urn to cover tlie ex\npenses and lie guaranteed every fa\ncouiiuitee rooms,\npress accommodations, etc.\nW. F'. R. Mills, of the Denvei Rua\niuess Men's league, presented the\nformal Invitation of Denver, lie\ngave assurances us to the location,\nclimate, scenery, facilities, etc., and\nrepeated tlie offer of 100 000\nSenator Teller supported those\nwho bad preceded him in all they had\nsaid about Denver.\nHe guaranteed there would tie\nrobbery of delegates by tlie hotels,\nlie said It would encourage Colorado\ndemocrats to have tlie convention in\nDenver. There was a rood demo\ncratic following in that state, and\nlie said \"Twice we have given that\nIncomparbale democrat. W. J. Bryan,\nuur electoral votes. We 'can do that\nigain, either Itiyan or some other\ngood democrut.\nSenator Teller was loudly ap\nplauded.\nor,\nan\nof\nSpeaking for Chicago, James Ham\nllton Lewis said that city would offer\na convention hall, rent free, and^Jfi,\nXNi cash for immediate delivery in\norder to secure the convention. If\nmore money was necessary to pay the\nactual expenses of the convention, It\nwould tie forthcoming. He spoke at\nlength of Lite central position of Chi\ncago and mentioned the many lintels.\nRepresentative Siierle.v, of Ken\ntucky, presented Louisville's claim.\n'While,\" he said, \"we have no\nsnow-capped mountains to lioust of,\nwe have other white things, and our\ngreen is more verdant and more fra\ngrant than any that can lie supplied\nby the valleys of Colorado.\nMr. Sherley said Louisville would\nfurnish fice Hie convention hall and\nwould guarantee 01 10,000 payable by\nJanuary 10 to meet the expenses of\nthe convention.\nThe claims for St. Paul were put\nforth by Charles D. D'Autremont,\nJr., a proxy delegate, who contended\nthat tiiat climate of St. Paul In sum\nmer time was far preferable to t hai\nof any other city farther south.\nOrchard on Rack.\nBoise, Idaho, lier 13.\u2014Clarence\nHarrow, the Chicago attorney who is\nconducting the defense of (\u00efeorge A\nPettlbone, had Harry Orchard, the\nstate s chief witness, on the rack for\ntwo hours and a hall today endeavor\ning to discredit ids testimony.\nThe cross-examination was rigid\nand effective in that Hie witness was\npictured as an Inhuman monster\nmurderer, bigamist, perjurer, gatnb\n1er. thief and Incendiary\nProfiting by the failure of Attorney\nRichardson In the Ilavwood trial\nshake the testimony of Orchard,\nDarr\u00ab w made little attempt to make\nthe witness contradict himself.\nTwice only during the day d'd lie\ntry to confuse Orchard In regard to\nhis testimony and each time lie\nfailed. Reading from the testimony\nof the Haywood trial, liai row en\nupjdeavored to make it appear that Hie\n\nI witness had changed Ids statements,\nUnit-[but Orchard forced Ills questioner to\nI read more of his testimony gl ven lie-;\nfoie, showing that Ids h-sttmouy had\nbeen the same at both trials.\nOrchard all but broke down when\nHawley aske I him If he had any per\nsonal enmity against Ids victims,\nnaming them one by one. ar:d in\neach case he said til\u00ab' he had n< r\nBe was especially affected when\nasked concerning McCormack and\nBeck at the Vindicator mine,\nwhom he said he thoughi a great\ndeal.\nIt, Harrow began his croaa-esuiulna\nUoo of Orchard at 11 -W o'clock, and\na before the adjournment 1 r the m-on\nrecess had drawn from him the fact\nthat before leaving Canada lie rad\nburned a cheese factory to codec In\nI\n\n\nI\nsorance and that when he left he\ntook with him another nun *if>\nAt the afternoon session tlie cr>>ss\nexamination of Orchard by Dirrow\nwas continued,\nj\nasked Harrow.\n\"I do not know.' was the answer.\n\"Do you expect to be tried *t ally\njl ,lr\n'When do you expect to be tried?\"\nH\u2014\n1\" never pleaded not guilty; I did\nnot plead at all.\"\nBarrow Took up tlie gambling\ncareer of Orchard, and then allowed\nthat the Hercule\u00ab mine, in which\nOrchard once owned a sixteenth in\nterest. Is now worth several million\ndollars. He was taken over the\nevents of the Oneur d'Alene*, ending\nwith Hie blowing up of the Bunker\nHill and Sullivan mill and the kill\ning of two men.\n\"And you did not know Moyer,\nHaywood or Petti hone?\" asked the\nattorney.\nHarrow then Jumped to Cripple\nCreek and asked Orchard concerning\nhis \"high grading\" in Hie Vindicat\nor, and the story of the killing of\nlieck and McCormack was reviewed\n\"And you didn't know Moyer,\nHaywood or Petlihone Hum?\" was\nasked again.\nThe same ixilnted question followed\nan examination In regard to or\nchard's second marriage when Ids\nwife and child were still living in\n\u00bbnads, und again alter he had fold\nof Hie mmbng of Neville's saloon to\ngel tlie insurance. Harrow ques\ntioned Orchard closely in regard to\nhts relations with D. C. Scott, a\nColorado detective ami lie admitted\naccepting i30 or to from the detec\ntive at various times.\nThe details of the 1 ndependence\nexplosion were narrated again, and\nthe witness told of the shooting of\nGregory. Tlie Bradley affair was\ntaken up before adjournment lids\nafternoon.\na\nMrs. lap'i Gilt In Idaho.\nMis. Russel Sage, notwithstanding\ntlie many misgivings of critics, Is\ndistributing the immense fortune of\nner miser husband In 11 very credit\nable manner. It seems.\nWhile alle Is Importuned for money\nby hundreds of undeserving *men and\nwomen and is bored by gift seekers\nOf every known brand and variety,\nvet she makes tirst-class selections In\nher lieatowals and seems to lie guided\nhy a desire to place her great fortune\nwhere It will do ttie most good. Very\nrecently she gave *2.7 ,000 to Hie Idaho\nindustrial Institute at Weiser, the\nsum of $10.1100 to la\u00bb used I 11 the erec\ntion of a Isi)s dormitory 10 .uoo for\na machine shop and $.'>,000 in the\npurchase of land upon which stu\nients may work for Hie support of\ntlie Institution.\n'lids Is tlie nucleus of what will\none dav he a magnificent, self-sup\nport big instil ut ion. if It is managed\nproperly, and will become a splendid\nmonument to the Sage foitune.\u2022 Po\natello Tribune.\nBryan Will get There.\nFt. Benton, Deo. 13. \u2014lion. David\nBrowne, chairman Jof the demo\ncratic state central committee, re\nvived tlie following telegram from\nthe New York World yesterday, after\nresident Roosevelt had Issued Ids\nstatement, re-affirming tlie declara\ntion that lie would not accept aj\nnomination tor a third term from\nthe republican convention next, year:\n\"New York, Doc. 12, 1907.\nlion. David U. Browne.\n\"Ft. Benton, Mont.:\nThe World would greatly appreci\nate an answer hy telegraph to this\nquestion: Iioes: the statement of\nPresident Boosevelt make It Inevlt-\nable that William J. Bryan shall bei\nnominated Jby tlie democratic party\nat 'the hext convention, or does It\nmake tlie field more open, thus\nchanging the democratic situation?''\nMr. Brown answered as follows:\n\"FT. Benton. Mont... Dec. 12, 1907.\n\"The World,'New York:\n\"Tlie \u00bbIr. tement made by President\nRoosevelt, docs not cfange the situa\ntion as far us the democratic candi\ndate is concerned, except, that In\nmy opinion, it. ^wlll practically Insure\nthe triumphant'election of William\nJ. Bryan.\nS' igriedj David (J. Brown. Chair\nman.\nAid Hankers il Good.\nWashington. Dec. 14. \u2014Comptroller\nof the Currency lUdgley states today\nthat at a conference with United\nStates Senator William Warner and\ni) H. I lean of Kansas City, this\nmorning, be told them In* was In\nthorough sympathy with the efforts\nto bring atiout tile reopening of till*\nNational Bank of Commerce of Kan\nsas City. Mo., at as early a date as\npossible: provided that the capital\nof the bank should la\u00bb completely re\nstored and largely increased; that\nttie bank tie provided with ample\ncash means at Its re-opening to meet\n)lt ,______ _\nGuthrie on his way to Texas, in\nTexas he will spend three or four\nday* with frfends. Then he will con\ntinue his trip to tiie South and will\nreturn to Liooolu on January IO.\nLeave your orders for artistic\njob printing with The Recorder.\nOnly the best work done.\nI .ill demands and that further. Hier*\nshould tie such a reorganization of\ndirectors of the bans tiiat tlie new\ntmard and officers should lie free from\nall responsibility for ttie suspension\nof the oid bank, and soon Id not only\nInspire but command such confidence,\nt/otii in Kansas City snd throughout\nthe He\u00bbt, t trat there would be no\ndoubt of tlie success of Hie reorgan\nI l/ed bank\nBryan on Long Journey\nLincoln. Neb., Dec. 14.\u2014William\nJ Itiyan will deliver an address u\nmembers of the Oklahoma Legis\nlature on IiecemberJI. stopping at\nFRIEND j FRIEND.\nThe personal reran nirndstiaiia of peo>\npie who have been cured of coogha and\ncolds by Chamtwrlain'a Cough Remedy\nhave done morv than all cite to make it a\n\u25a0tapir article of trade and commerce over\na Urge part of the civilized world.\nM\nCHAKTKIj NO. UOSO.\nM MiPiiKusos President.\nN I. Andkkws, Vice Pit-s.\n11. ti. Kino, Cashier.\nRay Edwakim. Asst. Cash.\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK\nSALMON. IDAHO.\nCAPITAL\nOOO.\nThis new Isuik 1 t-qulppt-o to\nserve its pat rons promptly in\nany <\\tparity wh> re 1 he wnIce*\nof a Isuik are required.\nDIRECTORS.\nJ. U. Sim iatr, A. .1 Mar nah, N.\nI Andrews, II ti, King. t,.\nE. Bowman, M. M. Mr\nPhcrann and E, H.\nEdwards.\n\"Just w\nCIGAR.S\nI\n1\nI\n1\ntickle the taste of smok\ners with my cigars.\nhave brands that have\nbeen tried and tested.\nhave large and small,\nstrong or mild.\nkeep them right,\nmoist enough.\nJust a few reasons why my\nCijars never disappoint\nW. H. Pyeatt, Ph. Q.\nDRUGGIST\nSalmon Idaho\nThe Montana\nand Idaho Stage\nand Forwarding\nCompany.\nlour and Six-Horse Concord\nCoaches from Redrock, Mon\ntana, to Salmon\nIdaho\nDAILY\nConnecting at Salmon for all tin*\nprincipal point* In the Salmon\nRivKKUut NTUY. including Indian\n1 rr\u00ab-k. Plu>- Creek, slioup Gibbons\nvllle. ciuillis, Custer, Clayton Bay\nhorse and Stanley Basin.\nA Isu making t Onnection for Lees\nburg and tlie Blackbird Copper Dis\ntrict. Merei* Cove, F orney. Yellow\nJacket and the great gold fields of\nPr\u00e4rie Basin. Thunder Mountain\nand all camps west of Salmon.\nOne of the best equipped\nlines in the West, carrying\npassengers, express and\nfreight.\nHave'your shipments mar\nked care of the Stage Com\npany, or W. B. Horn, man\nager. Redrock, Montana.\nOffice Rear Postoffice.\nJ. A. Herndon. Agt.\nFor full information inquire\nW. B. Horn,5upt.\nREDROCK, MONTANA.","height":"20544","width":"15408"}}
